---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Nav from "../components/Nav.astro";
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro";

const title = "Docs — Mercek";
const description =
  "Get started with Mercek: connect your AWS profiles, activate scopes, and start working with your ECS clusters from the desktop.";

const sections = [
  {
    id: "install",
    h: "Install",
    body: [
      "Mercek runs on macOS (Apple Silicon and Intel) and Linux (.deb / .AppImage). Download it from the home page and open it — on macOS, move it to Applications first.",
      "It doesn't create an account or run a server. The first time you open it, it reads the AWS profiles already on your machine.",
    ],
  },
  {
    id: "credentials",
    h: "How credentials work",
    body: [
      "Mercek uses your existing AWS credential chain. That's the same ~/.aws/config and ~/.aws/credentials the AWS CLI uses, so SSO, assume-role, MFA, and static keys all work.",
      "Mercek never copies or stores your credentials. Resolved secrets from Secrets Manager or SSM are shown as ARNs in the UI and aren't written to disk.",
    ],
  },
  {
    id: "scopes",
    h: "Activate scopes",
    body: [
      "A scope is a profile and region together. Mercek reads nothing from an account until you activate a scope for it, so you control what it touches.",
      "Activate as many as you want. Mercek discovers the clusters, services, and tasks across all active scopes and shows them in one tree.",
    ],
  },
  {
    id: "reading",
    h: "Read-only by default",
    body: [
      "Browsing, metrics, logs, and the topology map are all reads. None of them change your infrastructure.",
      "Writes are explicit: scaling, forcing a deploy, stopping a task, updating a service, and rolling back. Each one shows a diff of what will change and waits for you to confirm.",
      "Opening an interactive shell into a running container (ECS Exec) runs from the task view. If the service doesn't have execute-command turned on yet, Mercek can enable it for you — which starts a new deployment — and then connects you to the container.",
    ],
  },
  {
    id: "agent",
    h: "Connecting an agent",
    body: [
      "The agent panel uses the Agent Client Protocol, so you can connect a coding agent such as Claude Code. The agent is read-only to AWS. It can read your ECS state and open screens in the app, but it can't change anything.",
      "When the agent suggests a change, Mercek opens the same diff dialog you'd use by hand, with the matching AWS CLI command beside it. You decide whether to apply it.",
    ],
  },
];
---

<Layout title={title} description={description} path="/docs">
  <Nav />
  <main class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-16 sm:px-6">
    <a href="/" class="text-[13px] text-accent">← back home</a>
    <h1 class="mt-4 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight">Getting started</h1>
    <p class="mt-3 text-[15px] leading-relaxed text-dim">
      Mercek is a desktop app for Amazon ECS. There's no setup beyond the AWS
      credentials you already have.
    </p>

    <nav class="mt-8 flex flex-wrap gap-x-4 gap-y-2 border-y border-line py-3 text-[13px]">
      {sections.map((s) => (
        <a href={`#${s.id}`} class="text-dim transition-colors hover:text-fg">{s.h}</a>
      ))}
    </nav>

    <div class="mt-10 space-y-10">
      {sections.map((s) => (
        <section id={s.id} class="scroll-mt-20">
          <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold tracking-tight">{s.h}</h2>
          {s.body.map((p) => (
            <p class="mt-3 text-[14px] leading-relaxed text-dim">{p}</p>
          ))}
        </section>
      ))}
    </div>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</Layout>
